<br>
HL2 and its generation are about the most realistic-looking games we've seen to date and yet they are still quite noticeably CG. There are still polygon seams and texture warping and the like. And I will maintain that nobody, even in movies, has made organic motion that looks natural. Look at the burly brawl. It's the current top of the line and it still looks really weird in places. Too floaty, too smooth, etc.<br>
<br>
When we can get photoreal humans who move in a realistic way, and textures that will never, ever blur or pixelate even when your face is right in them, then we'll have reached the limits of polygon graphics.<br>
<br>
Then we'll move on to voxels. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mofo09@polykarbonbbs>mofo09</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/1/03 12:17 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=738.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   yo yo yo</span><hr size=1> it is a fact that no game on the ps2 has used it to its full extent graphics wise and as well as gameplay, and looking at gt 4 i wonder what ps2 can really do????<br>
