rranged well by talented artists; everything must be textured convincingly so that any repetition isn't obvious; the lighting and perspective must be correct so that things really &quot;belong&quot; in the game-world. And of course, everything has got to be animated flawlessly, and the physics engine must allow objects to interact just as they would in real-life. If something goes wrong for even half a second - a distant object pops into view, a punch goes straight through an opponent's head, the frame rate suddenly drops - the illusion is shattered.<br>
<br>
But are more realistic graphics always desirable? While they can help increase the feeling of immersion in games (particularly racing and sports games, which attempt to mimic real-life events), there will always be room for more stylised art styles, such as those seen in games such as Sonic, Rez, and the various &quot;cell-shaded&quot; games like Jet Set radio.<br>
<br>
And although it's been said many-a-time: gameplay is always more important than graphics. Metropolis Street Racer on the Dreamcast (and, later, its Project Gotham cousins on the X-Box) impressed people <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>initially</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> because of it's incredibly accurate recreations of London, Tokyo and San Francisco; but it was the game's length, gameplay, and the innovative &quot;kudos&quot; sytstem which made it really great (though admittedly the kudos idea wasn't exactly perfected first time round).<br>
<br>
Another racing game, F-Zero X on the N64, doesn't have very detailed graphics, but its insane speed is what makes that game fun - unless a more powerful console was used, greater detail couldn't have been achieved without sacrificing the speed. Burning Rangers on the Saturn has been criticised because the console couldn't handle some of its more ambitious flame effects, but the character and level design, replay value and fun gameplay still make it one of my favourite games. <p>---<br>
